Order book data is a fundamental data type for assessing the available liquidity in a market, but the high level of granularity and frequent number of bid/ask updates can make it difficult to maintain a full view of the order book state over time. In this example, we showcase how a Websocket connection can be used to construct a real-time view of the order book state by combining a single point-in-time snapshot with a stream of subsequent updates.

### Define OrderBook functions


```python
class OrderBook:
    def __init__(self):
        self.bids = {}
        self.asks = {}

    def update_from_snapshot(self, snapshot):
        self.bids = {float(level['price']): float(level['size']) for level in snapshot['bids']}
        self.asks = {float(level['price']): float(level['size']) for level in snapshot['asks']}

    def update_from_tick(self, tick):
        # Update bids
        for bid in tick['bids']:
            price = float(bid['price'])
            size = float(bid['size'])
            if size == 0:
                self.bids.pop(price, None)
            else:
                self.bids[price] = size

        # Update asks
        for ask in tick['asks']:
            price = float(ask['price'])
            size = float(ask['size'])
            if size == 0:
                self.asks.pop(price, None)
            else:
                self.asks[price] = size

    def plot_order_book(self, ax):
        fig = plt.gcf() 
        fig.set_size_inches(28, 7) 

        # Get the bid and ask prices and sizes
        bid_prices, bid_sizes = zip(*sorted(self.bids.items(), reverse=True))
        ask_prices, ask_sizes = zip(*sorted(self.asks.items()))

        # Plot the bids and asks
        ax.bar(bid_prices, bid_sizes, width=0.5, color='green')
        ax.bar(ask_prices, ask_sizes, width=0.5, color='red')

        title_fontsize = 20
        label_fontsize = 16
        ax.set_title('\n' + market.upper() + '\n Order Book\n', font='arial', fontsize=title_fontsize)
        ax.set_xlabel('\nPrice', font='arial', fontsize=label_fontsize)
        ax.set_ylabel('Volume\n', font='arial', fontsize=label_fontsize)
        ax.grid(True, linestyle='dotted', linewidth=0.5, color='gray')
        ax.tick_params(axis='both', which='major', labelsize=12)

    def plot_table(self, ax):
        # Convert bids and asks to DataFrame
        bids_df = pd.DataFrame(list(self.bids.items()), columns=['Bids (Price)', 'Bids (Volume)']).sort_values(by='Bids (Price)', ascending=False)
        asks_df = pd.DataFrame(list(self.asks.items()), columns=['Asks (Price)', 'Asks (Volume)']).sort_values(by='Asks (Price)')

        # Concatenate top 10 and bottom 10
        middle_row = pd.DataFrame([['...', '...']], columns=['Bids (Price)', 'Bids (Volume)'])
        bids_df = pd.concat([bids_df.head(10), middle_row, bids_df.tail(10)], ignore_index=True)
        asks_df = pd.concat([asks_df.head(10), middle_row.rename(columns={'Bids (Price)': 'Asks (Price)', 'Bids (Volume)': 'Asks (Volume)'}), asks_df.tail(10)], ignore_index=True)

        # Align lengths
        bids_df = bids_df.reindex(range(len(bids_df)))
        asks_df = asks_df.reindex(range(len(asks_df)))

        # Concatenate bids and asks side by side
        table_data = pd.concat([bids_df, asks_df], axis=1)

        # Create the table
        ax.axis('off')
        the_table = ax.table(cellText=table_data.values, colLabels=table_data.columns, loc='center')

        # Set cell height
        cell_height = 0.032 # Example height; adjust as needed
        for key, cell in the_table.get_celld().items():
            cell.set_height(cell_height)
        the_table.scale(1, 1.45) 
        
    def get_plot_image(self):
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(24, 6))
        self.plot_order_book(axes[0])
        self.plot_table(axes[1])
        buf = BytesIO()
        plt.savefig(buf, format='png')
        buf.seek(0)
        plt.close(fig)
        return buf
```

### Transforming Functions


```python
def is_snapshot(message):
    return message.get("type") == "snapshot"

def transform_snapshot(snapshot):
    return {
        'bids': [{'price': bid['price'], 'size': bid['size']} for bid in snapshot['bids']],
        'asks': [{'price': ask['price'], 'size': ask['size']} for ask in snapshot['asks']]
    }

def transform_tick(tick):
    return transform_snapshot(tick)  
```

### Open Websocket connection and plot results


```python
# Message handling function
def on_message(stream, message):
    global order_book
    message = orjson.loads(message)
    if is_snapshot(message):
        order_book.update_from_snapshot(transform_snapshot(message))
    else:
        order_book.update_from_tick(transform_tick(message))

    # Capture plot as an image
    img_buf = order_book.get_plot_image()

    # Display plot as an image
    img_html = f'<img src="data:image/png;base64,{base64.b64encode(img_buf.getvalue()).decode()}" />'
    display(HTML(f'<div style="display: flex; justify-content: center; width: 100%; height: 100%;">{img_html}</div>'))

    # clear_output(wait=False)

    sequence_id = int(message['cm_sequence_id'])
    # print(sequence_id)
    # if sequence_id >= 5:
    #     os.kill(os.getpid(), signal.SIGINT)
```


```python
if __name__ == '__main__':
    order_book = OrderBook()
    stream = client.get_stream_market_orderbooks(markets=market)
    stream.run(on_message=on_message)
```
